2. Categorical

(1) Frequency table

The most basic statistical summary of a list of objects or numbers is its distribution. For example, with categorical data, the distribution simply describes the proportion of each unique category. The sex represented in the heights data. Work same as pd.crosstab() or pd.groupby().mean() in python. 카테고리에 따른 단일 기술통계량 값을 확인할 때 사용한다.

library(dslabs)
library(ggplot2)
library(tidyverse)
## -- Attaching packages --------------------------------------- tidyverse 1.3.1 --
## v tibble  3.1.4     v dplyr   1.0.7
## v tidyr   1.1.3     v stringr 1.4.0
## v readr   2.0.1     v forcats 0.5.1
## v purrr   0.3.4
## -- Conflicts ------------------------------------------ tidyverse_conflicts() --
## x dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
## x dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()
heights %>% 
  group_by(sex) %>%
  count() %>%
  ungroup() %>%  # Make data frame again, same as reset_index() in python 
  mutate(MEAN = round(n/sum(n), 3)) %>% 
  select(sex, MEAN)
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   sex     MEAN
##   <fct>  <dbl>
## 1 Female 0.227
## 2 Male   0.773

This two-category frequency table is the simplest form of a distribution.

(2) bar plot
murders %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = region, fill = region)) + 
  geom_bar()

data(murders)
tab <- murders %>%
count(region) %>%
mutate(proportion = n/sum(n))
tab 
##          region  n proportion
## 1     Northeast  9  0.1764706
## 2         South 17  0.3333333
## 3 North Central 12  0.2352941
## 4          West 13  0.2549020
tab %>% 
  ggplot(aes(region, proportion)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")

(1) Cumulative distribution function(eCDF)
(2) Histogram
heights %>%
  filter(sex == "Female") %>%
  ggplot(aes(height)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

heights %>%
  filter(sex == "Female") %>%
  ggplot(aes(height)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1) # Change bin

heights %>%
  ggplot(aes(height)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = sex), binwidth = 1, col = "black") +
  xlab("Female heights in inches") +
  ggtitle("Histogram")

##### (3) Smoothed density

heights %>%
  filter(sex == "Female") %>%
  ggplot(aes(height)) +
  geom_density()

heights %>%
  filter(sex == "Female") %>%
  ggplot(aes(height)) +
  geom_density(fill="blue")

heights %>%
  ggplot(aes(height)) +
  geom_density(aes(fill=sex), alpha = 0.5)

##### (4) The normal distribution

index <- heights$sex == "Male"
x <- heights$height[index]
m <- mean(x)
s <- sd(x)
c(average = m, sd = s)
##   average        sd 
## 69.314755  3.611024
(5) Quantile-quanitle plot(QQ-plot)

내가 비교하고자 하는 분포가 정규분포와 어느정도 유사하는지 확인하는 그래프.
- pnorm : return probability of CDF if input is phi - qnorm : return phi of CDF if input is probability - qnorm(p, mean = n, sd = v) : can make any normal distribution

qnorm(0.975, mean = 5, sd = 2)
## [1] 8.919928
p <- seq(0.05, 0.95, 0.05) # 비교하고자 하는 quantile
sample_quantiles <- quantile(x, p) # dataset 의 qauntile
theoretical_quantiles <- qnorm(p, mean = mean(x), sd = sd(x)) # 정규분포의 quantile

qplot(theoretical_quantiles, sample_quantiles) + geom_abline()

z <- scale(x)
sample_quantiles <- quantile(z, p)
theoretical_quantiles <- qnorm(p)
qplot(theoretical_quantiles, sample_quantiles) + geom_abline()

heights %>% filter(sex=="Male") %>%
  ggplot(aes(sample = height)) +
  geom_qq()

heights %>% filter(sex=="Male") %>%
  ggplot(aes(sample = height)) +
  stat_qq() + 
  stat_qq_line()
